            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 14-year-old girl with a slight, athletic build who presents to the pediatric neurology clinic accompanied by her mother. She stands about 162 cm tall and weighs approximately 52 kg. Her dark brown hair is pulled back into a ponytail, and she wears a medical ID bracelet on her left wrist — a detail her mother insisted upon after her second seizure episode. Despite her diagnosis, {patientName} carries herself with a quiet confidence, though today she appears mildly anxious, fidgeting with the strap of her school backpack.\n\n{patientName} is a passionate artistic girl who loves drawing manga-style comics and plays volleyball on her school's junior team. She is a dedicated 9th-grade student with strong grades, particularly in art and biology. She lives with both parents and a younger brother (age 10) in a suburban home. She has an active social life and spends weekends with a close group of friends. Sleep is occasionally irregular due to late-night screen time — a known seizure trigger her neurologist has repeatedly addressed.\n\nHer seizures first began approximately 18 months ago. She experienced sudden episodes of staring blankly for 15–30 seconds, during which she was unresponsive to verbal cues. These were initially dismissed as daydreaming at school. The episodes escalated eight months ago when she suffered her first convulsive (tonic-clonic) seizure at home, lasting roughly 2 minutes, witnessed by her mother. She was post-ictally confused and fatigued for about 30 minutes afterward.\n\n{patientName} reports occasional auras before her convulsive episodes — a brief strange feeling in her stomach and a sense of déjà vu. She denies any significant head trauma, febrile seizures in infancy, or meningitis. She does not smoke, drink alcohol, or use any illicit substances. Her menstrual cycles started at age 12 and are regular; her physician has carefully noted the potential teratogenic risk of valproic acid and discussed it with both {patientName} and her mother.\n\nOn today's visit, {patientName} appears alert and oriented. She is cooperative and articulate about her symptoms. Her vitals are stable. Her mother reports that {patientName} has been seizure-free for the past three months on the current medication regimen, though she still occasionally forgets to take her evening dose — a source of ongoing family tension."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:cd4beb18-2b29-473e-8655-9951c7e4b43c",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
